@startuml ssd-cache-versioning
' End-to-end sequence: builder writes v2 (new content-addressed key),
' updates the catalog (NOTIFY in the same txn), DPs receive the
' invalidation via LISTEN (push) or the 5-second TTL pull fallback,
' and a query lands on v2 while an in-flight query on v1 completes
' against v1's mmap (POSIX guarantee).

title Shard v2 rollout: build -> catalog -> DP invalidation -> next query

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam defaultFontName Helvetica
skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam ArrowFontSize 11
skinparam NoteFontSize 10
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

actor "client" as client
participant "index_builder" as builder
participant "object_store" as os
database "shard_catalog\n(Postgres)" as catalog
participant "query_dp\n(holds v1 warm)" as dp
database "shard_tier\n(SSD)" as ssd
participant "kernel" as kern

== Build v2 ==

builder -> builder : content_hash =\nsha256(serialised_index)[:16]
builder -> os : PUT s3://{bucket}/{tenant}/{dataset}/\n  {shard_id}-{content_hash_v2}.bin
activate os
os --> builder : 200 OK
deactivate os
note over builder, os #LightYellow
  Content-addressed key.
  Never overwrites v1's key.
  Idempotent: same bytes -> same hash.
  Gated on RB_SHARD_VERSIONED_URIS;
  flag-off path writes the legacy
  {INDEXES_PREFIX}/.../indexes/{date}/
  layout instead.
end note

== Publish ==

builder -> catalog : BEGIN
builder -> catalog : INSERT shard_catalog (..., shard_uri=v2_uri)
builder -> catalog : NOTIFY catalog_updates\n  {tenant, dataset, shard_id, shard_uri}
builder -> catalog : COMMIT
note right of catalog
  NOTIFY rides the same transaction.
  If COMMIT fails, the NOTIFY is
  also discarded -> never inconsistent.
end note

== Push invalidation ==

catalog -> dp : LISTEN delivers {shard_id, shard_uri}
note right of dp
  DP invalidates its cached
  list_shards result for the dataset.
  v1's SSD-tier entry stays cached
  (no eviction) until W-TinyLFU
  decides it.
end note

== Mid-query consistency (in-flight on v1) ==

client -> dp : (earlier) POST /v1/query
activate dp
dp -> dp : _cache_get(shard_id_v1) HIT
dp -> kern : index.search() -> page faults on v1
note over dp, kern #LightBlue
  v1's open fd pins the inode.
  The mmap stays valid even if
  the SSD tier later unlinks the file.
end note
kern --> dp : pages from v1
dp --> client : results from v1
deactivate dp

== Next query, after NOTIFY ==

client -> dp : POST /v1/query
activate dp
dp -> catalog : list_shards (newest first)
catalog --> dp : v2 (newest), v1, ...
dp -> dp : _cache_get(shard_id_v2) MISS
dp -> ssd : shard_tier.fetch(shard_id_v2, v2_uri)
activate ssd
ssd -> os : GET v2_uri
activate os
os --> ssd : bytes
deactivate os
ssd -> ssd : write tmp + atomic rename
ssd --> dp : local_path for v2
deactivate ssd
dp -> kern : faiss.read_index(v2, IO_FLAG_MMAP)
dp -> dp : index.search() -> page faults on v2
dp --> client : results from v2
deactivate dp

== TTL fallback (push lost) ==

note over catalog, dp #LightYellow
  If the LISTEN connection dropped
  between BEGIN and the next query,
  the DP re-reads list_shards anyway
  whenever its cached result is older
  than RB_CATALOG_FRESHNESS_S (5s).
  Worst-case staleness is bounded.
end note

@enduml
